===Central Coast===
The Central section spans the [[Matagorda Bay]] and [[Victoria, Texas|Victoria]] areas down to the [[Port Aransas, Texas|Port Aransas]] and Corpus Christi areas.<ref name="TPWD: CTC">{{cite web | url=http://www.tpwd.state.tx.us/huntwild/wild/wildlife_trails/coastal/central/ | title=Great Texas Coastal Birding Trail - Central Texas Coast (CTC) | publisher=Texas Parks and Wildlife Division | accessdate=10 Nov 2009}}</ref> 

The Central Coast section offers many bird species of its own. The [[Matagorda Bay]] area contains [[American Oystercatcher]]s, [[Hudsonian Godwit]]s, and [[White-rumped Sandpiper]]s. The [[Corpus Christi, Texas|Corpus Christi]] area features [[Groove-billed Ani]]s, [[Olive Sparrow]]s, [[Long-billed Thrasher]]s, [[Couch's Kingbird]], [[Black Skimmer]]s, and [[Black-crowned Night Heron]]s.<ref name="TPWD: CTC"/>

===Lower Coast===
The Lower section spans the [[South Padre Island]] and [[Brownsville, Texas|Brownsville]] areas up the Rio Grande to Laredo.<ref name="TPWD: LTC">{{cite web | url=http://www.tpwd.state.tx.us/huntwild/wild/wildlife_trails/coastal/lower/ | title=Great Texas Coastal Birding Trail - Lower Texas Coast (LTC) | publisher=Texas Parks and Wildlife Division | accessdate=10 Nov 2009}}</ref>

The Lower Coast section which lies around the [[Rio Grande]] offers its own species diversity. [[South Padre Island]] and the [[Laguna Madre]] areas feature [[Magnificent Frigatebird]]s, [[Bridled Tern]]s, and [[Cory<U+2019>s Shearwater]]. Further up the Rio Grande around [[Santa Ana National Wildlife Refuge|Santa Ana]] and [[McAllen, Texas|McAllen]] one can find [[Elf Owl]]s, [[White-tipped Dove]]s, [[Green Jay]]s, [[Green Kingfisher]]s, and [[Mississippi Kite]].<ref name="TPWD: CTC"/> The endangered [[Brown Pelican]] is found especially on South Padre Island in addition to other locations on the coast. The inland areas around [[Zapata, Texas|Zapata]] are home to [[White-collared Seedeater]]s, [[Lesser Goldfinch]], [[Ash-throated Flycatcher]]s, and [[Black-tailed Gnatcatcher]]s.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tpwd.state.tx.us/huntwild/wild/wildlife_trails/coastal/lower/zapata/ | title=Lower Texas Coast Wildlife Trail (LTC): Zapata Loop | publisher=Texas Parks and Wildlife Department | accessdate=11 Nov 2009}}</ref>

==Nature Preserves==
Major nature preserves along the trail system including the following:
:[[Anahuac National Wildlife Refuge]], [[Aransas National Wildlife Refuge]], [[Attwater Prairie Chicken National Wildlife Refuge]], [[Big Boggy National Wildlife Refuge]], [[Big Thicket]] National Preserve, [[Brazoria National Wildlife Refuge]], [[Laguna Atascosa National Wildlife Refuge]], [[Texas Point National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref name="TPWD: GTCBT">{{cite web | url=http://www.tpwd.state.tx.us/huntwild/wild/wildlife_trails/coastal | title=Great Texas Coastal Birding Trails | publisher=Texas Parks and Wildlife Department | accessdate=10 Nov 2009}}</ref>

The Aransas National Wildlife Refuge is the largest of the national refuges in Texas.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fws.gov/refuges/land/pdf/AnnLandsReport_2008.pdf | title=Annual Report of Lands Under Control of the U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service | date=30 September 2008 | pages=15<U+2013>27 | publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service}}</ref> The Big Thicket National Preserve features the largest number of wetlands boardwalks in the state (75).<ref>{{cite magazine | title=Top 10 Boardwalks | publisher=Texas Parks & Wildlife Magazine | author=Smith-Rodgers, Sheryl | date=July 2006 | url=http://www.tpwmagazine.com/archive/2006/jul/ed_9/}}</ref>

==Ecotourism==
The trail systems lie in and around numerous communities along the coast, many of which specifically cater to ecotourists. Annual nature festivals are held in [[Rockport, Texas|Rockport]], Port Aransas, [[McAllen, Texas|McAllen]], [[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]], [[Harlingen, Texas|Harlingen]], and [[Mission, Texas|Mission]] attracting large numbers of visitors each year.<ref name="BWD"/><ref name="Wauer (2004), p. 19">Wauer (2004), p. 19.</ref> The system includes numerous important urban nature centers including the [[Armand Bayou Nature Center]], [[Baytown Nature Center]], the [[Corpus Christi Botanical Gardens and Nature Center]], the South Padre Island Birding and Nature Center, and the [[Texas City Prairie Preserve]].

